  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks against money laundering. One of the most comprehensive and widely recognized international efforts to combat money laundering is led by the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, an intergovernmental body established in 1989. The FATF sets global standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system.\n\n### Key International Frameworks and Laws:\n1. **FATF Recommendations**:\n   - The FATF has issued **40 Recommendations** that provide a comprehensive framework for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. These recommendations are recognized as the global standard and have been adopted by over 200 countries and jurisdictions.\n\n2. **UN Conventions**:\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: This is one of the earliest international treaties addressing money laundering, particularly in the context of drug trafficking.\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: Also known as the Palermo Convention, this treaty includes provisions to combat money laundering linked to organized crime.\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Corruption (2003)**: This convention requires member states to take measures to prevent and criminalize money laundering related to corruption.\n\n3. **European Union Directives**:\n   - The EU has issued several **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLDs)**, which require member states to implement measures to prevent money laundering and terrorist financing. The latest iteration is the **6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD)**, which strengthens criminal penalties and expands the scope of money laundering offenses.\n\n4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**:\n   - The Basel Committee has issued guidelines for banks to implement measures to prevent money laundering, such as **Know Your Customer (KYC)** and **Customer Due Diligence (CDD)** procedures.\n\n5. **Wolfsberg Group Principles**:\n   - The Wolfsberg Group, an association of global banks, has developed principles and guidelines to help financial institutions combat money laundering, particularly in private banking and correspondent banking.\n\n### Key Principles in International Anti-Money Laundering Laws:\n- **Criminalization of Money Laundering**: Countries are required to criminalize money laundering and establish effective legal frameworks to prosecute offenders.\n- **Customer Due Diligence (CDD)**: Financial institutions must verify the identity of their customers and understand the nature of their transactions.\n- **Reporting Suspicious Transactions**: Financial institutions are required to report suspicious transactions to relevant authorities.\n- **International Cooperation**: Countries are encouraged to cooperate in investigations, asset recovery, and extradition related to money laundering.\n\nWhile these frameworks provide a global standard, enforcement varies by country. Many nations have enacted domestic laws to comply with these international standards, but the effectiveness of anti-money laundering efforts depends on implementation and enforcement at the national level.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
